John Edwards: Foreign language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland’s private schools have maintained their academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with a string of commendable academic results, reinforced both individually and collectively by sport, art, music and community engagement.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, sponsored by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), are dedicated to providing the best quality of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to acquire a broad and deep knowledge, as well as the career orientation and status of their students as global citizens.
As an educational sub-discipline that can design and run the school’s unique curriculum, we see modern foreign languages continuing to be a popular topic of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to someone in the language he understands, his words will enter his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words that come out will go into his heart.”
This is a compelling message that we don’t just rely on English when it comes to establishing relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exams this year, we can see that foreign languages are leading in the rankings with the best scores in private schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language students scored higher than A.
Data collected from SCIS’ 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students who scored above A in Chinese, besides 72 percent who studied German, 69 percent who studied French and 63 percent who studied Spanish also scored A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are moving towards seeing foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will not be without in the future.
Elective foreign language subjects are being considered as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) majors in private school curricula as well as elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Skills and Careers Council in 2014 showed that among the reasons employers have difficulty finding people, there is a shortage of foreign language skills.
Therefore, foreign language skills are becoming more practical to equip young people to enter the career in the future.
With more career prospects needing foreign languages, these skills become practical in an increasingly flat world.
No matter how people choose to work, if they learn a second language, they will gain a real advantage in the future when they have such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly in the native language of the people themselves, a polyglot will obviously lead the test.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to practice a simple assembly passage in another foreign language, and only French was the only foreign language to account for a single number, 15 percent.
This is why investing in foreign language teaching is so important for children today.
Being multilingual, especially in the languages of developing economies, equips children with a brighter potential for finding a real job.
In Scotland, each school teaches different foreign languages.
Some schools will focus on more modern foreign languages, while others will teach those that are considered important to the UK in view of 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever their interests, there are a variety of foreign languages to choose from within private schools, along with a team of professional teachers.
Scottish private schools focus on providing an academic environment that prepares and equips children with the skills they need for success, no matter what the future holds.
It is undeniable that, in an international business environment, foreign languages will continue to be a very important factor for the future of the country, which should be replicated in education.
In fact, modern foreign languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Private schools will continue to offer this opportunity to young Scots: diversity and excellence.
There's no other choice.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council for Private Schools.
