North Korea says there's 'no way' to disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that sanctions remain in place to deepen its distrust of the United States and that under these circumstances there is no way it will unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho, speaking during the annual session of the UN General Assembly, said North Korea had taken "multiple goodwill measures" over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test sites and pledging to not proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we do not see the same move from the U.S. side,” he said.
“If we cannot trust the U.S. side, then we will not be able to ensure our national security with confidence, and under such circumstances, there is no way we will unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s familiar complaint that Washington refuses to disarm in “phases” and that North Korea would receive corresponding benefits from doing so step by step, his remarks have the remarkable point of not rejecting unilateral nuclear disarmament as Pyongyang has refused before.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12. In the statement, Kim pledged efforts toward “denuclearization on the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised to ensure North Korea’s security.
North Korea is still trying to find a way to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States insists that Pyongyang give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease draconian international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearization first" and increases pressure with sanctions to achieve its goals in a coercive manner, even opposing the "declaration of an end to the war", Ri said.
“The notion that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just a wild dream of those who know nothing about us.
“But the problem is that the sanctions that are still in place continue to lose our trust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, as the U.S. leader presented at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he mentioned three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: “If the negotiating party on nuclear disarmament is South Korea, not the United States, then the denuclearization talks on the Korean Peninsula will not be at an impasse as they are today.”
But Ri’s tone was different from last year’s, when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s launch of missiles at the U.S. mainland was inevitable on a suicide mission after Trump called Kim “rocket man.”
Last year at the United Nations, Trump threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, but this year he lavished praise on Kim for taking courageous steps to disarm, but he also stressed that much work remains to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a deadline for this: “Two years, three years or just five months doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its efforts.
But U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “Security Council sanctions must continue to be vigorously and uncompromisingly enforced until we can confirm the results of complete denuclearization, finally, with verifiable evidence.”
The Security Council has agreed to strengthen sanctions on North Korea since 2006 to stem funding for its nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo held talks with Ri on the sidelines of official U.N. General Assembly meetings and said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the final result has not been very positive.
He left Pyongyang after a visit in July and said there had been progress in the talks, but just hours later North Korea accused the foreign minister of making "gangster-like demands."
North Korea has pledged to take part in a meeting with South Korean President Moon Jae-In this month aimed at dismantling a missile test base and a nuclear complex if the United States makes the same move.
He said Kim directed that the "similar move" he was seeking was the security assurance Trump had pledged during talks in Singapore and to move toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
In an effort to combat a culture of machine learning pressure, with night owl students drinking coffee instead of water, a new course at Harvard University this year has encouraged all college students to get more sleep.
Students who study at the world’s number one university often don’t know the basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, is also a specialist at Women’s Hospital and Brigham designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
The inspiration for starting this course came after he participated in a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on the learning process.
“At the end of our conversation, a female student came up to me and said, ‘Why did you learn this in your final year?’
She said no one told her about the importance of sleep, which really surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students how the importance of good sleep habits enhances academic and athletic performance, while improving their overall health.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the school decided to introduce the course after discovering students were severely sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course includes a wide range of interactive tasks.
In one section there is a dorm room image, in which students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, workout machines, and books to learn about how caffeine, light, and sleep deprivation affect sports performance, as well as the importance of forming a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants were asked how long-term sleep deprivation could increase their risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then, the university campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this course cannot immediately change students’ behavior.
But we believe they have a right to know — just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” Czeisler added.
He said: “The proud culture of ‘night owl students’ still exists, at the same time that modern technologies and increasing pressure on students lead to sleep deprivation is an increasingly serious problem.
Ensuring adequate, quality sleep should become a student’s ‘secret weapon’ against stress, exhaustion and anxiety – even to avoid weight gain, because a lack of sleep puts the brain into a state of hunger, which leads to constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying biology, chemistry and physics, helped Czeisler design the course and took one of last year’s classes during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course helped him “open his eyes” and inspired him to make an effort to call for a school-wide course.
He hoped that the next step would be to suggest that all graduate students take a similar degree program before starting to compete in the main course.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students consider setting bedtime, wake-up time alarms, and be aware of the harmful effects of ‘blue light’ emitted from electronic screens and LEDs, which can disturb your circadian rhythm, leading to trouble sleeping.
