Yearbook: The inventor of the Geiger Counter
Take a page from the "Sunday Morning" Yearbook: On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago, and CONTINUELY...future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, inventing the foundation for the device known as the Geiger Counter.
Since then, the Geiger Counter has not only become a pillar of science, but also a pillar of popular culture. The following example is a dialogue in the film "Bells of Coronado", released in 1950, starring the scientist and cowboy king Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What is this?"
Rogers: “This is the Geiger Counter, which is used to locate radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these headphones on, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radiation in the mineral.”
Evans: “Yes, there’s a clicking sound coming from here!”
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days after his 63rd birthday.
However, the invention that bears his name remains forever.
