The National Trust overhears the secret life of bats.
A new study is being conducted on a plot of land in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use natural landscapes to hunt for food.
It is hoped these findings will shed light on the behaviour of this unique flying mammal and guide future conservation activities.
The study, led by National Trust for Scotland, tracked the journeys of common bats, soprano pipistrelles, brown-eared bats and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the study grounds to monitor the activity of these bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
The expert will analyze all sound recordings and determine the frequency of bat sounds and the purpose of playing the sounds of specific bat genera.
Then maps and habitat reports of bats will be made to get a detailed picture of their behavior according to the natural landscape.
Rob Dewar, NTS conservation adviser, hopes the results will help determine which habitats are most important for bats and how each species lives in that environment.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management activities, such as grassland planting, and how best to conserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect bat bean platforms and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and light systems, flytrap paper, some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as pet cat attacks can also pose a risk to bats.
Bats are not completely blind.
However, due to the habit of hunting at night, the ears are more useful than the eyes when snooping and catching prey.
They use an extremely sophisticated echolocation technique to identify obstacles on the flight path.
NTS is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, and attaches special importance to bats.
The organization has ten trained professionals who regularly carry out surveys, examinations and sometimes participate in animal rescues.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave estates in Dumfries and Galloway. It is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The land manager, David Thompson, said the land was ideal territory for them.
"Threave is a great habitat for bats," he said.
“We have a lot of old buildings, a lot of big trees and good habitat.
But there is still a lot of mystery about bats, so the work here and at other facilities will help us better understand what bats need to thrive further."
He stressed the importance of checking the life of bats before conserving in the grounds, because accidentally destroying their breeding grounds can kill up to 400 females and vomiting, almost completely destroying the population.
Bats are protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their pods.
Elisabeth Ferrell, of the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, encouraged the community to get involved.
“We still need to learn more about bats, and with many species, we don’t know how far apart their populations are.”
